{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"393403dc-73b0-45ac-b7e8-c231d000f762","content":"## 3. GitHub Environment Setup\n\nCreate a **`nuget`** environment in your repo under **Settings → Environments**. This scopes the OIDC token and lets you add protection rules (e.g., require approval before publish).\n\n## How it works\n\n- No `--api-key` is needed — `dotnet nuget push` automatically uses the OIDC token from the `id-token: write` permission when NuGet.org recognizes the trusted publisher configuration.\n- You publish by pushing a tag: `git tag v1.0.0 && git push --tags`\n\n## Remaining steps on your side\n\n1. Register the trusted publisher on nuget.org (owner: `myorg`, repo: `mylib`, workflow: `publish.yml`, environment: `nuget`)\n2. Create the `nuget` environment in GitHub repo settings\n3. Ensure your `.csproj` has `<PackageId>`, `<Version>`, and other package metadata\n\nThat's it — no secrets to manage or rotate.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65be9021-35d1-4b5a-9117-c1241cd31ad3","outputTokens":233,"requestId":"B809:2B6299:D1E5AD:F0798C:69F2A8BC"},"id":"647054e8-4a56-429b-9604-5870fd94277c","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:56:38.493Z","parentId":"62d3402e-cb94-49d5-99f6-f34de9790068"}
